04181nam a22005655i 9780226562278DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226562278  a(DE-B1597)525040  a(OCoLC)648760887  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH360.5b.M38 2010eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a576.82221 aMcShea, Daniel W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBiology's First Law :bThe Tendency for Diversity and Complexity to Increase in Evolutionary Systems /cRobert N. Brandon, Daniel W. McShea. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b2 halftones, 5 line drawings, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Zero-Force Evolutionary Law -- t2. Randomness, Hierarchy, and Constraint -- t3. Diversity -- t4. Complexity -- t5. Evidence, Predictions, and Tests -- t6. Philosophical Foundations -- t7. Implications -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLife on earth is characterized by three striking phenomena that demand explanation: adaptation—the marvelous fit between organism and environment; diversity—the great variety of organisms; and complexity—the enormous intricacy of their internal structure. Natural selection explains adaptation. But what explains diversity and complexity? Daniel W. McShea and Robert N. Brandon argue that there exists in evolution a spontaneous tendency toward increased diversity and complexity, one that acts whether natural selection is present or not. They call this tendency a biological law—the Zero-Force Evolutionary Law, or ZFEL. This law unifies the principles and data of biology under a single framework and invites a reconceptualization of the field of the same sort that Newton’s First Law brought to physics. Biology’s First Law shows how the ZFEL can be applied to the study of diversity and complexity and examines its wider implications for biology. Intended for evolutionary biologists, paleontologists, and other scientists studying complex systems, and written in a concise and engaging format that speaks to students and interdisciplinary practitioners alike, this book will also find an appreciative audience in the philosophy of science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBiocomplexity. 0aBiodiversity. 0aEvolution (Biology)xPhilosophy. 0aEvolution (Biology). 0aScience. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abiodiversity, biology, ecosystems, evolution, complexity, adaptation, organism, environment, diversity, variety, natural selection, zfel, zero-force evolutionary law, constraint, hierarchy, randomness, nonfiction, science, nature, philosophy, modularity, drift, measures, population, species, habitat, distinctness, macroevolution, heredity.1 aBrandon, Robert N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022656225440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226562278423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226562278/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles